\begin_layout Standard
One of the most important considerations in American voting behavior is
 party identification.
 It is intended to measure a person's affinity for a particular party 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "campbell1960theamerican"

\end_inset

.
 Partisan attachment is meant to be more than just a temporary connection.
 It should be resistant to change, but previous research has debated the
 stability of party ID.
 Previous work on aggregate partisanship stability produced conflicting
 answers.
 MacKuen, Erikson, and Stimson (1989) find that aggregate macropartisanship,
 a measure of Democrats over the total number of Democrats and Republicans,
 is much more responsive to short term influences than previously imagined
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mackuen1989macropartisanship"

\end_inset

.
 Green, Palmquist and Schickler (1998) respond with a critique of the methodolog
y used by MacKuen et al., finding aggregate macropartisanship to be much
 more stable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "green1998macropartisanship"

\end_inset

.
 Green et al.
 further explain these results in their book 
\emph on
Partisan Hearts and Minds
\emph default
 where national macropartisanship is shown to change more permanently in
 response to economic evaluations and presidential approval 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "greenpartisan"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast to the individual level where shocks should not upset party
 ID, aggregate macropartisanship should respond to economic and political
 evaluations because new groups of people are entering the macropartisan
 pool.
 Evaluations have a longer term effect because they are setting a political
 attachment for new groups which produce strong ties to certain political
 parties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous studies have debated the stability of macropartisanship either
 on the individual level or the aggregate level but always on a national
 level.
 Measures of macropartisanship on the state level have not existed until
 recently.
 Early measures disaggregated CBS/NYT national polls asking party ID questions
 to arrive at measures of partisanship at the state level 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wright1985measuring"

\end_inset

.
 Recent efforts have used polls such as the CCES to estimate state level
 partisanship 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "carsey2010newmeasures"

\end_inset

 and multilevel regression with postratification (MRP) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pacheco2011usingnational"

\end_inset

, but these efforts only measure state level partisanship back to the early
 1970s.
 Enns and Koch have recently utilized MRP and CBS/NYT polls to measure state
 partisanship back to the 1950s (2013)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "enns2013publicopinion"

\end_inset

.
 Extending state level partisan measurement creates an opportunity to examine
 the change in state partisanship during politically important times.
 Pushing the starting line back to the 1956 allows us to examine changes
 in party ID as the country went from ideologically unsorted parties to
 ideologically homogenous and polarized parties that we experience now.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the past 50 years, the partisan tilt of many states has changed dramaticall
y.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Methods and Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, I introduce the methodology and then the data used.
 To examine changes in aggregate macropartisanship at the state level, I
 use time series analysis used by Green et al.
 in 
\emph on
Partisan Hearts and Minds
\emph default
 (2002).
 Green et al.
 use a model where macropartisanship is a function of macropartisanship
 lagged one time period, economic evaluations, and presidential approval.
 Economic evaluations and approval used to explain changes in macropartisanship.
 The model assumes that these two measures are driving macropartisanship
 change.
 Party dummies are also added to economic evaluations and approval to indicate
 which party is occupying the White House when change is occurring.
 A healthy economy operating under a Democratic administration can explain
 an increase in macropartisanship, while a well performing economy under
 a Republican can explain a decrease in the number of Democratic identifiers
 compared to Republican identifiers.
 It's a similar process for approval where positive judgments of the ruling
 party can modify the party identifications in the electorate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lagged variable for macropartisanship serves a crucial role of determining
 how permanent any change is to the time series.
 A value closer to 1 indicates that change is more permanent (Green et al.
 2002).
 A value near zero means that any change in macropartisanship dissipates
 quickly.
 Green et al.
 find that the lagged macropartisanship variable on an individual level
 is very low (Green et al.
 2002, p.
 65).
 This fits well for individuals.
 A single person should be unlikely to change his or her party identification,
 especially over the short term.
 Party ID is meant to indicate a long term affinity and not just short range
 views or a voting history.
 If voters quickly adapted to changes in the economy or presidential approval,
 party ID would be less stable and probably less useful as a measure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the story is opposite when considering aggregate macropartisanship.
 Looking at the electorate on a larger scale, newly joining people should
 be set in their ways.
 If partisanship doesn't change much for an individual, then the changes
 we see should be caused by the partisan leaning of people and groups entering
 the electorate.
 A generation of young voters might have an affinity towards the Republican
 Party and this identification will carry forward into future elections.
 Aggregate change appears more permanent because it accounts for a larger
 pool of people having a long lasting tie to a party.
 Affirming this view, Green et al.
 find the lagged coefficient to be around .9 depending on the model specification
 (2002, p.
 98-99).
 An economic downturn or an unpopular president can damage a party in the
 eyes of those coming into the electorate and these experiences shape their
 partisanship for a long time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
National aggregate macropartisanship is as stable according to Green et
 al, but how does state level aggregate macropartisanship compare? For macropart
isanship to change in the country overall, it should also experience change
 at a state level.
 Given the large changes in partisanship and voting behavior of some states
 since the 1950s, there should be variation between states in the stability
 of party identification.
 Economic performance is not equal across the country.
 By looking at changes on a state level, it is possible to gauge how differences
 in economic performance influenced aggregate macropartisanship.
 Presidential approval also varies by state and might influence the permanence
 of partisanship in voters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to analyze differences in aggregate macropartisanship change across
 states, I use a random effects model.
 State macropartisanship is still a function of previous state macropartisanship
, economic evaluations, and presidential approval.
 However, I allow each state to have its own intercept and coefficient for
 lagged macropartisanship.
 Setting up the model in this way allows the full pool of states to be considere
d, but each state can have its own value for macropartisan stability.
 Economic and approval variables are modeled to have the same coefficient
 across all states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the methods used by Green et al.
 in 
\emph on
Partisan Hearts and Minds
\emph default
, I require three pieces of data measured at the state level.
 The first and most obvious requirement is state level measures of macropartisan
ship.
 I use Enns and Koch's state partisanship data which includes all states
 and spans from 1956 to 2010 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "enns2013publicopinion"

\end_inset

.
 In order to calculate state partisanship, they pooled national surveys
 which asked party ID questions.
 Instead of just disaggregating the polls by year and state, Enns and Koch
 use individual and state level characteristics along with MRP to more precisely
 estimate state partisanship.
 MRP uses individual characteristics like race, age, and gender along with
 survey answers to generate predictions for how particular groups are likely
 to respond.
 
\end_layout

