 Michigan, Ohio, and Pennsylvania hardly changed at all over the 55 years.
 Northeastern states like New York, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Vermont
 tilted slightly more towards the Democrats over time.
 The regional and state variation appears to show that aggregate party ID
 stability depends on a local political context.
 
