\begin_layout Standard
The next important piece of data required is economic performance.
 Green et al.
 use consumer sentiment from the University of Michigan which is available
 at the national level (Green et al.
 2002).
 Consumer sentiment is not available on a state level, but other economic
 measurements are collected over a long period of time.
 The Bureau of Economic Analysis tracks Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for
 states since the 1960s, but their methodology changed in 1997 in a way
 that makes it unwise to compare values across this threshold.
 State GDP is also less desirable than other measures since it might be
 less tangible to the voters involved.
 The effects of a rise or decline in state GDP might be less noticeable
 than other economic measurements.
 One benefit of a measure like consumer sentiment used by Green et al.
 is that it has a more subjective element to it where people are judging
 the economy based on conditions they experience.
 I use state personal income change as an economic measurement.
 It stands as a good compromise between data availability and gets at the
 more subjective measure of the economy that is present in the consumer
 sentiment index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last piece of data needed in presidential approval.
 National polling on presidential approval is ubiquitous enough to allow
 for slicing approval into time units smaller than years.
 This is not the case for presidential approval polling on the state level
 currently.
 The most comprehensive collection of state level approval polling is the
 U.S.
 Officials Job Approval Ratings data set (JARs) compiled by Beyle, Niemi,
 and Sigelman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "beyle2002gubernatorial"

\end_inset

.
 It contains thousands of polls for presidential approval taken within in
 a state.
 For purposes of this study, only explicit approval questions are used.
 When a state is polled multiple times in one year, I average the approval
 and disapproval results for that year.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A drawback of the JARs dataset for this project is that it does not include
 very many polls earlier than the 1990s.
 The bulk of the polls are from the 2000s.
 As a result, I focus less on including approval since it only speaks to
 a narrow time frame.
 Going forward in extending this project, it should be possible to disaggregate
 national polls that include the state of the respondent in order to construct
 a more complete time series of state level presidential approval.
 
\end_layout

